<p>As summer approaches, shoppers refresh their wardrobes for the season, putting pressure on retailers across the UK to pull out all the stops and maximize sales. With customer demand rising and appetite for new items growing, retailers won't want to fall behind competitors.</p>
<p>The past couple of months have been eventful for UK retailers, who have faced their share of challenges, from rising customer expectations to unexpected disruptions. Retail giant M&amp;S has made a strong comeback, reporting a full recovery and resuming online sales after a major cyberattack that had largely impacted revenue.</p>
<p>With that in mind, here's a look at recent highs and lows shaping retail technology headlines, and what to expect next.</p>

<h2>Celebrating loyal customers</h2>
<p>It's more important than ever for retailers to create tailored, personalized experiences for customers. Loyalty schemes and benefits programs are a powerful tool to strengthen customer relationships, encourage repeat purchases, and build a sense of community and exclusivity.</p>
<p>Supermarket giant Tesco found a creative way to celebrate its Clubcard anniversary, hosting a 90s-themed nightclub experience that gave its most loyal customers the chance to earn extra Clubcard points and prizes in a memorable way.</p>
<p>Athletic apparel may seem like a crowded market, but gym wear retailer Gymshark is continuing to build momentum. The brand recently announced its first-ever loyalty program, rewarding customers with experience points for interacting with the brand, whether through purchases or completing a training program in its workout app, giving customers the feel of being part of the Gymshark community.</p>
<p>Fashion and lifestyle retailer ASOS has also sharpened its approach to loyalty. After backlash over closing a number of customer accounts under a new returns rule, ASOS responded by launching a new tiered loyalty program, offering exclusive benefits and rewards that grow in value each time a customer shops, a continued investment in customer experience and satisfaction.</p>

<h2>AI enhancing the customer experience</h2>
<p>Artificial intelligence is quickly becoming a core part of modern retail operations. More retailers are using AI to streamline processes, boost efficiency, and create personalized, engaging customer experiences.</p>
<p>Toy retailer Mattel announced a new strategic partnership to support AI-powered products and experiences, incorporating ChatGPT into its product development to better engage audiences, spark innovation, and showcase its commitment to cutting-edge AI in product development and customer interaction.</p>
<p>To boost in-store operations, coffee giant Starbucks is deploying a new generative AI tool to assist associates with task efficiency, whether completing orders, resolving mechanical issues, or providing real-time conversational responses. The goal is to strengthen the connection between barista and customer while reducing wait times and improving service overall.</p>

<h2>Blending the omnichannel experience</h2>
<p>Retailers are continuing to transform the customer journey by seamlessly integrating digital convenience with immersive in-store experiences, keeping consumers engaged across every touchpoint.</p>
<p>Skoda recently became the first European automotive brand to offer an Amazon car showroom, giving customers real-time vehicle availability and the ability to explore the full Skoda range before choosing a retailer. Customers can select their model through the Amazon site or app and are then connected to their preferred retailer, saving time and creating a more convenient car-buying journey.</p>
<p>Beauty retailer Superdrug has developed a Beauty Playground immersive experience, first unveiled at its Westfield Stratford flagship store and expected to extend to 30 of its top-performing stores by August. The concept includes "try me" tables, ring-light stations for creating beauty content, and interactive zones for discovering new brands, all supported by in-store associates offering advice.</p>
<p>These examples show how brands are driving innovation through omnichannel strategies, making shopping more engaging, convenient, and customer-focused.</p>

<h2>Looking ahead</h2>
<p>With consumer expectations rapidly evolving, it's important to implement innovative solutions to stay ahead of the curve. At Teamwork Commerce, we believe deploying smart retail technology significantly enhances operational efficiency, elevates customer experience, and drives sales. We're looking forward to seeing how the rest of the summer unfolds and how retailers grow through the season.</p>
